<font color="#FF0000">I'D PULL THE PILL ON HIM..</font><br>
<tt>Fri Dec  5  4:11:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Let's see if I have this right... if anyone in your unit does not meet up to your ideals of Brave_Fart_of _The_World you would &quot;Pull the pin on them&quot; interesting thought but I for one am man enough to admit to being scare out of my mind at times in 'Nam. Never share a foxhole with a man braver than you.. it'll get you killed. The interesting part is every 'Nam vet I know admits to the world but more important to HIMSELF that he was scare out of his wits by real combat... Becuase they , self included, were scare AND very lucky we made it home. <br><br>
  Late July 1969 the 101st made a CA &lt; Combat Assault &gt; into the Ashu valley. My company was part of that CA an the LZ was a hot as I had ever seen. WIth us that day was a kid from New York City, he was in 'Nam not of choice.. no not drafted but a judge gave him a choice bteween jail &amp; 'Nam. When we hit that LZ this tough little street kid from NYC who thought he was so tough discovered what the rest of already knew... this is scary sh*t in anyones book. The firefight lasted only 20 mins or so very intense and deadly but then it was over we were trying to account for everyone. We discovered this kid... I say that with affection 'cause almost all of us were under the age of 21... we found him under a downed tree that the prep arty had blown down. And yes indeed he had pissed himself , scared shaking and frighten beyond words. NO ONE, NOT ONE of the men in my company gave him a lot of sh*t about it, explained he can't do this... some got mad but all realized that somewhere down inside of all of us we wished we could dive under that log with him to get out of the ak fire raking the lz.. realized that each of us the first time firefight did stupid stuff...<br>
granted we all did not piss ourself's... I think we were too damn scare to do even that. After this guy calmed down, like the rest of us from the emotions of the firefight he blended in with the rest of My Squad. Never again did he do as he did that day and no one ragged him about it either. <br><br>
 Second week of Sept 1969 found my company doing the usual out hump'h the bush when we ran into an NVA ambush. Once again the firefight was intense and brief. During the firefight three men died. Two were killed at the inital bust of fire from the ambush, my squad on point returned fire<br>
which caused the enemy to withdraw, at a price. When the fight was over the price of that ambush was clear, that very same KID from New York City lay dead, he had taken several KA47 hits. That SCARED kid, had stood his ground, that scare 19 year old had proven to be as much of a man as ANY OF US.<br>
He didn't play hero or John Wayne , he had just done his job as best he could, as we all did. How many other would have died that day had he not been there , how many other men would have fallen had someone pulled the pin on him ? And once again he had made us MAD AS H... Mad at his death, mad as H at the NVA wanting to get our hands on them to make them pay for killing him. I remember even those in the unit who were mad as hell at him for diving under that log, now mad as hell at the NVA, at the war, at death itself. I watched these 19 year old MEN mad as hell at him yelling at his dead body as we carried him to an extraction point, all mad as hell that he didn't get under cover in time, but with tears flowing down OUR faces as we cried our guts out... <br>
'cause we too were scared and we had lost a Friend.<br><br>
 Pulling the pin on someone is the loss of humanity in the first place, if there are lessons of war to be learned it is the depth of compassion &amp; trust we have for our fellow human beings. Lessions of fears over come, of being scared to death but being able to manage your fears during life and death events combat or not. Lessions of just what kind of human YOU are, not just the brutal 19 year old with an M16 but the MEN combat had turned us into. No one that day in Sept 1969 thought any less of those who cried at the deaths that day, it was part of a war &amp; becoming the Men we are today.<br><br>
Gary 'J.' <br>
Co B 1/327 inf 101st '68-71
